1f923.title: Rolling on the Floor Laughing
aliases: Rolling on the Floor Laughing Face
1f923.description: A yellow face with a big grin and scrunched, X-shaped eyes, tilted on its side as if rolling on the floor laughing (the internet acronym ROFL). Sheds two tears and tilts right on most platforms. Often conveys hysterical laughter more intense than 😂 Face With Tears of Joy. Microsoft's design previously featured a smiley with hands and feet. Rolling on the Floor Laughing was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f925.title: Lying Face
1f925.description: A yellow face with raised eyebrows, enlarged eyes, slight frown, and long nose, indicating it’s telling a lie in the manner of Pinocchio. Like that character, Facebook's design features a wooden nose. May represent lying, a liar, and other concepts of deceit and dishonesty to varying degrees of intensity. Sometimes used to convey disbelief (e.g., You must be kidding) or feeling abashed (e.g., as if caught in the act of lying). Lying Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f924.title: Drooling Face
1f924.description: A yellow face, usually shown with closed eyes and raised eyebrows, with saliva drooling from one corner of its mouth. Often used to show desire for a person (sexy, attractive) or object (e.g., delicious food). May also represent someone is tired or sleeping. Not to be confused with 😋 Face Savoring Food or 😪 Sleepy Face. Samsung's design previously featured a startled facial expression. Drooling Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f922.title: Nauseated Face
1f922.description: A sickly-green face with concerned eyes and puffed, often red cheeks, as if holding back vomit. May represent physical illness or general disgust. Not to be confused with 🤮 Face Vomiting. Differs from other smileys conveying sickness, including 🤒 Face With Thermometer (used especially for colds and flus) and 🤕 Face With Head-Bandage (physical injury). Nauseated Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f927.title: Sneezing Face
1f927.description: A yellow face with scrunched, X-shaped eyes sneezing or blowing its nose into a white tissue, as if from a cold or allergies. Often depicted with a crumpled-looking mouth. May also represent someone in an emotional state wiping away tears, as at a wedding. Sneezing Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f920.title: Cowboy Hat Face
1f920.description: Yee-haw! A yellow smiley wearing a wide-brimmed, brown-leather cowboy hat. Its smile varies across platforms. May convey a sense of exuberance, whimsy, confidence, adventure, or other sentiments. Several vendors, including Apple, feature the same expression as their 😃 Grinning Face With Big Eyes. Cowboy Hat Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Face With Cowboy Hat” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f921.title: Clown Face
1f921.description: A classic circus or birthday clown. Features white face makeup, a red nose, exaggerated eyes and smile, and two tufts of hair (red or blue). May convey that someone is silly or foolish or that something is creepy or scary. Clown Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f5a4.title: Black Heart
1f5a4.description: A heart shaded completely black. May be used to express morbidity, sorrow, or a form of dark humor. Not to be confused with the Heavy Black Heart or Black Heart Suit which are both red. Black Heart was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f91a.title: Raised Back of Hand
1f91a.description: A raised hand, showing the reverse side of the palm. May be paired with the forward-facing raised hand emoji. Raised Back of Hand was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f91e.title: Crossed Fingers
aliases: Hand With Index and Middle Fingers Crossed
1f91e.description: A fingers crossed emoji which displays the index (first) finger crossed over the middle (second) finger. Commonly used as a gesture indicating luck, or to show desire of a favorable outcome. This emoji is displayed with an additional finger on Samsung devices. Crossed Fingers was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Hand With Index and Middle Fingers Crossed” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f919.title: Call Me Hand
1f919.description: A hand with thumb and little (pinky) finger extended, making a traditional phone-like shape. May be used in conjunction with a face to suggest “call me” (please). Not to be confused with the sign of the horns or the shaka sign (which does not yet have an emoji representation). Call Me Hand was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f933.description: A mobile phone held up to take a selfie (photo of the person holding the phone or camera). Generally represented as a disembodied arm holding a mobile phone. Selfie was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f926.title: Person Facepalming
1f926.description: A hand shown pressing against the head of a person, commonly written as facepalm. Used to display frustration or embarrassment at the ineptitude of a person or situation. May be used in a similar context to the acronym SMH (shaking my head), or in relation to the Picard Facepalm meme. Person Facepalming was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Face Palm” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f937.title: Person Shrugging
1f937.description: A person shrugging their shoulders to indicate a lack of knowledge about a particular topic, or a lack of care about the result of a situation. Displays as raised shoulders, sometimes in conjunction with raised arms and flat hands. The shrug gesture in text (emoticon) form is known as a shruggie and typed as: ¯\_(ツ)_/¯ The Unicode character Shrug ("Person Shrugging") does not specify a gender though is displayed as a woman on most major platforms. See also Woman Shrugging or Man Shrugging. Person Shrugging was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Shrug” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f930-1f3ff.description: This version of the 🤰 Pregnant Woman emoji has the 🏿 Dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Black Skin Tone on supported platforms. Pregnant Woman: Dark Skin Tone was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f936.title: Mrs. Claus
1f936.description: Mother Christmas, more commonly known as Mrs. Claus, is the wife of Santa Claus. Displayed as an older woman with glasses and a festive red and white bonnet. See also: Christmas emoji list. Mrs. Claus was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Mother Christmas” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f936-1f3fb.title: Mrs. Claus: Light Skin Tone
1f936-1f3fb.description: This version of the 🤶 Mrs. Claus emoji has the 🏻 Light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Pale Skin Tone on supported platforms. Mrs. Claus: Light Skin Tone was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f57a.title: Man Dancing
1f57a.description: A man dancing, added as a gender pair for the 💃 Woman Dancing. Shown on most platforms in a 70s-era suit, and one hand in the air in a disco-dancing style. Man Dancing was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93a.title: Person Fencing
1f93a.description: A person shown in the sport of fencing, with a Rapier-style sword, mask, and protective clothing. Person Fencing was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Fencer” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f938.title: Person Cartwheeling
1f938.description: A person doing a cartwheel, representing the sport of gymnastics. Person Cartwheeling was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Person Doing Cartwheel” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93c.title: People Wrestling
1f93c.description: Two people in the sport of wrestling. People Wrestling was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Wrestlers” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93d.title: Person Playing Water Polo
1f93d.description: A person shown in water with a ball, playing the sport of water polo. Person Playing Water Polo was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Water Polo” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93d-1f3fb.description: This version of the 🤽 Person Playing Water Polo emoji has the 🏻 Light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Pale Skin Tone on supported platforms. Person Playing Water Polo: Light Skin Tone was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f939.title: Person Juggling
1f939.description: A person juggling between three and five colored balls. The person shown in this emoji generally has the appearance of a man, and wears a hat on most major platforms. Person Juggling was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Juggling” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f939-1f3fb.description: This version of the 🤹 Person Juggling emoji has the 🏻 Light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Pale Skin Tone on supported platforms. Person Juggling: Light Skin Tone was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f98d.title: Gorilla
1f98d.description: A gorilla, the powerful, black-haired great ape. Variously depicted in full profile on all fours facing left or as a friendly, cartoon-styled gorilla face looking straight ahead. Apple, WhatsApp, Facebook, and Microsoft’s designs feature a full gorilla, as a silverback, with strong shoulders and reddish forehead. Google, Samsung, and Twitter’s designs feature a black and gray gorilla face with a neutral expression and prominent forehead and jaw. Facebook’s design previously featured only a gorilla face. Gorilla was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f98a.title: Fox
1f98a.description: A friendly, cartoon-styled faced of a fox, the cunning canine, looking straight ahead. Depicted as an orange fox  face with a black nose, pointed ears, and shaggy, white cheeks. Often used with an affectionate or playful tone (e.g., slang, foxy). Does not have a full-bodied fox emoji counterpart. Available as an Apple Animoji. Fox was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Fox Face” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f98c.title: Deer
1f98c.description: A deer, a fleet-footed, hoofed mammal whose males (bucks, stags) generally have antlers. Variously depicted as a light-brown deer in full profile on all fours facing left or as a deer face looking straight head; both depictions feature large, branched antlers. May be used to represent elk, moose, antelope, or reindeer, especially in connection with Christmas. Apple, Microsoft, WhatsApp, and Facebook's designs feature a deer in full profile; Google, Samsung, and Twitter's designs feature a deer face. Google’s deer has a red nose, as Rudolph the Red-nosed Reindeer. Apple and WhatsApp’s deers are white-tailed. Deer was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f98f.title: Rhinoceros
1f98f.description: A rhinoceros, a large mammal with one or two massive horns on its nose. Generally shown in light gray with two horns, depicted in full profile on all fours or as a rhinoceros head looking left. Resembles the white or black rhinoceros. Apple, Microsoft, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs feature the full animal; Google, Samsung, and Twitter’s designs feature only a rhinoceros head. Facebook’s design previously featured only a rhinoceros head. Rhinoceros was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f987.title: Bat
1f987.description: A bat, the flying mammal of the night. Variously depicted as a brown, black, or gray bat, with wings outspread and pointy ears, facing forward or left. Often used in association with Halloween, vampires, and Batman. Google’s bat is purplish in color, bearing two fangs. Samsung’s bat was previously brown, Facebook’s gray. Bat was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f985.title: Eagle
1f985.description: A bald eagle, the majestic bird of prey with brown feathers and distinctive white head. Generally depicted facing left, with its wings outspread and talons out, as if swooping down to seize prey. Commonly associated with the United States, whose national emblem is the bald eagle. May be used for other eagles and birds of prey (e.g., hawks) more generally. Google’s eagle has its wings tucked in, as if perched on a branch. Twitter’s design shows only the bust of an eagle. Apple’s 📰 Newspaper features its eagle on its masthead. Eagle was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f986.title: Duck
1f986.description: Quack! A duck, a waterbird with webbed feet. Depicted as a male (drake) mallard in full profile facing left, standing on its legs with gray and brown feathers, a yellow bill, and its distinctive green head. May be consumed in the form of a 🍗 Poultry Leg. Occasionally used as a substitute for the F-word, due to rhyming and Apple's iPhone autocorrect. Samsung’s design previously featured a yellow rubber ducky. Duck was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f989.title: Owl
1f989.description: An owl, the hooting, large-eyed bird of the night. Depicted as a reddish-brown owl, as a great horned owl, facing forward, Shown with large, round, gold-rimmed eyes, feet curled on or as if on a branch, wings tucked in, and its distinctive, horn-like tufts of feathers. May be used to represent wisdom. Popularly used in connection with the hip-hop artist Drake. Apple and Microsoft’s owls are on a branch. Microsoft’s owl previously resembled a barn owl, Samsung’s was purple. Owl was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f98e.title: Lizard
1f98e.description: A lizard, a scaly reptile with a long tail. Depicted as a light-green lizard on all fours from above, generally looking left with large eyes, a lightly textured or colored back, and toes outspread, as a gecko. May be used for a variety of wild and pet lizards. Google’s lizard was previously brown. Lizard was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f988.title: Shark
1f988.description: A shark, a large, stealthy fish with many teeth. Generally depicted as a gray shark in full profile facing left, as a tiger, bull, or great white shark hunting in the water. Shown with a white underside and three gills, its pointed nose and teeth-lined mouth curving down to a sharp dorsal fin and long, pointed tail. Not to be confused with 🐬 Dolphin. Shark was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f98b.title: Butterfly
1f98b.description: A butterfly, a beautiful winged insect whose larva is a caterpillar. Depicted with its wings outspread, as a blue-and-black morpho butterfly or orange-and-black monarch butterfly. May be used to represent a moth and ideas of beauty and happiness. Samsung’s butterfly previously resembled a monarch. Butterfly was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f940.title: Wilted Flower
1f940.description: A flower that has wilted, or is dying. Generally depicted as a limp, faded red rose drooping over the to the right on a dried-out, green stem, shedding a petal. May be used to express such sad sentiments as heartbreak, though sometimes with a sense of irony. Sometimes used to represent a rose or other flower, with positive connotations. Not to be confused with 🌹 Rose. WhatsApp's flower suggests a wilted 🌻 Sunflower; Twitter's a 🌷 Tulip, as Microsoft and Samsung's previously did. Facebook's flower was previously orange. Wilted Flower was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f95d.title: Kiwi Fruit
1f95d.description: A kiwifruit, or Chinese gooseberry, with its fuzzy, brown skin sliced open to show its light-green flesh, white core, and black seeds. May be associated with New Zealand, whose residents are nicknamed Kiwis, after the bird. Kiwi Fruit was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Kiwifruit” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f951.title: Avocado
1f951.description: A pear-shaped avocado, sliced in half to show its yellow-green flesh and large brown pit. Ready for toast, guacamole, or millennial jokes. Avocado was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f954.title: Potato
1f954.description: A whole potato—such as a russet, used for baking, mashing, or frying—shown with a few eyes on its golden-brown skin. Not to be confused with the roasted sweet potato. Potato was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f955.title: Carrot
1f955.description: A whole, bright orange carrot, topped with long green leaves, as if freshly plucked from the garden. Some platforms feature a longer, thinner carrot, others a shorter, more bulbous one. Carrot was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f952.title: Cucumber
1f952.description: A long, green cucumber with bumpy skin. Resembles its derived product, a pickle or gherkin, on many platforms, except on Apple and WhatsApp, which depict it with light-green, seed-y slices. Cucumber was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f95c.title: Peanuts
1f95c.description: The pod of the peanut, shown in its rounded, grooved, light-brown shell. Apple depicts a pair. May be used for peanut butter as well as other edible nuts (e.g., almonds) or metaphorical ones, including slang for “crazy” and “testicle.” Peanuts was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f950.title: Croissant
1f950.description: The flaky, golden-brown crescent of a croissant, a breakfast pastry associated with France and Austria. Croissant was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f956.title: Baguette Bread
1f956.description: The long, thin loaf of a baguette, with scoring on its golden-brown crust. A bread commonly associated with France. Baguette Bread was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f95e.title: Pancakes
1f95e.description: A stack of breakfast pancakes, topped with a pad of butter and maple syrup oozing down its golden-brown sides, onto a plate on some platforms. Associated with the Christian observance of Shrove Tuesday, or "Pancake Day." Pancakes was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f953.title: Bacon
1f953.description: Strips of crispy, fatty, reddish-brown bacon, as fried for breakfast. Depicted as a pair on most platforms. Bacon was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f959.title: Stuffed Flatbread
1f959.description: A flatbread, like pita, stuffed with lettuce, tomato, and/or meat. Resembles a doner kebab, falafel, shawarma, or gyro sandwich, popular in the Middle East and the Mediterranean. Apple and WhatsApp add red onion and cucumber. Not to be confused with the Burrito. Stuffed Flatbread was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f95a.title: Egg
1f95a.description: An egg, most commonly displayed as a chicken egg with a white or light brown shell. May be used in cooking. Egg was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f958.title: Shallow Pan of Food
1f958.description: A flat, shallow, black pan with side handles, containing saffron-colored rice, vegetables, a leg of poultry, and/or shrimp and lemon slices. Commonly associated with paella, a traditional dish from Spain. May be used for eating, cooking, dining, and meals more generally. Apple's version of this emoji is considered to be representative of the traditional ingredients from Valencia. Samsung previously displayed this emoji as a Korean hot pot. Shallow Pan of Food was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f957.title: Green Salad
1f957.description: An undressed garden salad in a bowl with leafy-green lettuce and other ingredients such as tomato, red onion, and black olives. Commonly associated with healthy eating and living. Google previously displayed a hard-boiled egg, removed in 2018 to make the salad vegan-friendly. Green Salad was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f990.title: Shrimp
1f990.description: A shrimp (prawn), a small crustacean with a long tail. Generally depicted as a reddish-orange shrimp (as cooked) in full profile facing left, with tiny eyes, many limbs, and its long antennae curling back as its long tail curls in. May be consumed in the form of 🍤 Fried Shrimp or 🥘 Shallow Pan of Food. Often used to represent seafood. The antennae of Apple’s shrimp curls under its body. The body of Facebook’s shrimp is straight. Google and Samsung’s shrimp previously faced right. Shrimp was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f991.title: Squid
1f991.description: A squid, an octopus-like sea animal with ten arms. Generally depicted as a pinkish-orange giant squid, facing forward or angled to the left, with a slender, arrow-like body, small eyes, and two, long arms raised up at its sides. Platforms generally depict six arms. Occasionally used to represent squid as a food item. Not to be confused with 🐙 Octopus, though their applications may overlap. Microsoft, WhatsApp, and Twitter’s squids are facing forward. Samsung’s squid was previously gray. Squid was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93c-1f3fb.title: Wrestlers, Type-1-2
1f93c-1f3fb.description: This version of the 🤼 People Wrestling emoji has the 🏻 Light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Pale Skin Tone on supported platforms. Wrestlers, Type-1-2 was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93c-1f3fc.title: Wrestlers, Type-3
1f93c-1f3fc.description: This version of the 🤼 People Wrestling emoji has the 🏼 Medium-Light Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Cream White Skin Tone on supported platforms. Wrestlers, Type-3 was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93c-1f3fd.title: Wrestlers, Type-4
1f93c-1f3fd.description: This version of the 🤼 People Wrestling emoji has the 🏽 Medium Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Moderate Brown Skin Tone on supported platforms. Wrestlers, Type-4 was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93c-1f3fe.title: Wrestlers, Type-5
1f93c-1f3fe.description: This version of the 🤼 People Wrestling emoji has the 🏾 Medium-Dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Dark Brown Skin Tone on supported platforms. Wrestlers, Type-5 was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f93c-1f3ff.title: Wrestlers, Type-6
1f93c-1f3ff.description: This version of the 🤼 People Wrestling emoji has the 🏿 Dark Skin Tone applied, which is displayed as a Black Skin Tone on supported platforms. Wrestlers, Type-6 was added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f95b.title: Glass of Milk
1f95b.description: A tall glass of white milk, as from a cow but also other mammals, nuts, or plants. Most platforms depict a glass filled near to the brim, but some show a glass half-full—or half-empty. Glass of Milk was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f942.title: Clinking Glasses
1f942.description: Two flutes of champagne or sparkling wine being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast (“Cheers!”). Samsung’s design suggests two glasses of white wine. Some platforms include stylized links to mark the clinking. See also Clinking Beer Mugs—and Bottle With Popping Cork for a refill. Clinking Glasses was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f943.title: Tumbler Glass
1f943.description: A short, flat glass, as used for brown liquors like whiskey or Scotch whisky. Apple and WhatsApp serve theirs neat, while other platforms include ice ("on the rocks"). Samsung's glass features the faint initials ONI, an apparent in-company easter egg. Tumbler Glass was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f944.title: Spoon
1f944.description: A silver spoon, as used to eat soup, cereal, or ice cream as well as serve food or stir drinks. Positioned at various angles across platforms. May be paired with Fork and Knife, Fork and Knife With Plate, and Bowl With Spoon. Spoon was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f6f5.title: Motor Scooter
1f6f5.description: A motor scooter, which may be displayed as any type of motorbike with or without a step-through frame. Distinct from the racing motorcycle, which is used for sport, not transport. Motor Scooter was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f6f4.title: Kick Scooter
1f6f4.description: A non-motorized scooter, with two wheels and handles. Kick Scooter was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Scooter” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f6d1.title: Stop Sign
1f6d1.description: A red, octagonal sign. Used in many countries as a stop sign. Stop Sign was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Octagonal Sign” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f6f6.title: Canoe
1f6f6.description: Canoe was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f94a.title: Boxing Glove
1f94a.description: A padded boxing glove, used in the sport of boxing. Usually red. Boxing Glove was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f94b.title: Martial Arts Uniform
1f94b.description: A white uniform used in marital arts such as judo or karate. Held together using a material belt. Known as keikogi in Japanese. Martial Arts Uniform was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f941.title: Drum
1f941.description: A drum shown with drumsticks. A percussion instrument which is likely to be displayed as a snare drum. Drum was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Drum With Drumsticks” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1f6d2.title: Shopping Cart
1f6d2.description: Shopping Cart was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name “Shopping Trolley” and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

0023-fe0f-20e3.title: Keycap Number Sign
0023-fe0f-20e3.description: A hash key, sometimes referred to as a pound key in the United States. Most commonly used online to make a hashtag (or hash flag) on social media sites. The Keycap Number Sign emoji is a sequence of the # Number Sign and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Keycap Number Sign was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.
